						               													<description>A tile-cooking game for 2 to 4  players by N&amp;eacute;stor Romeral Andr&amp;eacute;s.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Did you ever wonder where all those tiles from hundreds of tile-laying games come from? Well, they&amp;rsquo;re made in the KILN. The KILN is the special, high-temperature oven in which you fire ceramics such as tiles made of clay.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;In KILN 2 to 4 players compete to manufacture tiles for the publishers of tile-laying games (such as nestorgames itself). All players share the same kiln, but each one has their own warehouse to store and sell the tiles to the publishers.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Material:&amp;#10;&amp;#10;- A board with a scoring track and an 8&amp;times;8 square grid (the rack) with an inner 6&amp;times;6 area (the kiln).&amp;#10;- Four 5&amp;times;5 grids with plastic coating (warehouses).&amp;#10;- 8 discs in 4 colours (2 each of red, blue, green, yellow)&amp;#10;- 7 grey discs (for advanced play),&amp;#10;- One black disc (goal marker).&amp;#10;- 4 erasable markers.&amp;#10;- 36 square tiles in four colours (red, blue, green, yellow) and one black square tile (the neutral tile), all the same size as the cells of the rack.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Game overview:&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Players take turns pushing tiles in the kiln, then copying the biggest shape of their colour to their warehouses, and optionally selling completed rows or columns for scoring. First to reach or cross the goal score wins. Draws are impossible.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;-description from publisher&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
